metadata.name: Tendencies #20
metadata.description:
Tendencies is the first in a set of collections based on a month-long study of Edward Zajec, one of the early pioneers of generative art in the 1970s.

Zajec's generative work was motivated by redundancy in his paintings: "The monotony of the manual task and the limited number of variations which I was able to produce in a given time made me realize the inadequacy of traditional methods in dealing with our present reality." Tendencies was inspired by ‚Äî and pays tribute to ‚Äî one if Zajec's earliest forays into generative creation: a work titled RAM 10 V.15, which was written on an IBM 1620 and programmed in FORTRAN.

The title of the collection itself is a reference to the first exhibition of Zajec's RAM series, while the number of editions minted referencing the year Zajec put plotter to paper.

Made in p5js
Created December 2022
By @christine_hall

metadata.name: NAZCA #150
metadata.description:
Real time animation (WebGL)
Variable dimension
2022

Nazca is a group of living glyphs made in the soil of the GPU. There are 17 figures that get combined and mixed over three layers. The figures vary in complexity but are generally created with vertical and horizontal lines only. Figures have at least one seed, some even have a seed per path. A seed is an oscillating pixel that can be compared to a square wave oscillator of audio synthesis and is usually followed by a path or a set of paths. The purpose of the paths is to send the pixels along the lines to make the figures visible through movement and to create a reduction to pure animation.

üëΩ Kim Asendorf

metadata.name: The Fire Within #255
metadata.description:
This project is a study of ink, everything is generated in code without using any texture. 
It is an attempt to capture the ink bleeding effect and the look of the traditional Chinese paintings that have texts on top with modern approaches.

objkt.name: THE WORD AFTER US: An AI poetry unreading #83

metadata.name: THE WORD AFTER US: An AI poetry unreading #83
metadata.description:
‚ÄúWhere in the world will words go, 
after us? How will they be arranged, 
and what will they sound like
when they arrive at their destination?
What will they be doing?
What will the world be doing?
Will the words be quiet or loud?
Will they be full of themselves,
or full of longing,
or full of longing‚Äôs opposite?‚Äù
 
An ars poetica on the future of literature and humanity. 
 
This project is a one-time generative poetry performance of a transhuman text by Sasha Stiles and her AI alter ego, Technelegy ‚Äì read and unread by an algorithm authored by Nathaniel Stern. Every hash transforms one of 353 lines of AI-written poetry from legible letters into wordless language, generating a unique textblock from millions of possible combinations; each algorithmic translation unwrites itself, forever. Press "s" to overlay and toggle the original line of verse, and watch its shapes and meanings degenerate ‚Äì or evolve ‚Äì into an infinite visual poem.
 
All minters will receive an airdropped broadside (mp4) of the entire original poem after the performance is complete. A 1/1 media-rich audiovisual version of THE WORD AFTER US will also be made available.

 
Poetic traits:
- 353 possible lines of generative poetry produced by a GPT-3 language model fine-tuned on Stiles‚Äô and Stern‚Äôs writing and research.
- 28 possible color palette combinations selected from Stern‚Äôs performative scanner art, with rare palettes including RGB, Hacker, Charcoal, and Chalkboard (black background).
- 6 possible fonts, including the premiere of Stern and Stiles‚Äô custom AI font, NNFT (Neural Network Font Type), developed for their ongoing collaboration, ‚ÄúMother Computer.‚Äù
- millions of layout and layering possibilities, including a rare ‚Äúspiral‚Äù effect.
- billions of animation attribute combinations, which carry on forever.

metadata.name: Mar de l√£ #7
metadata.description:
"Once upon a time, in a land far, far away, there was a magical kingdom known for its beautiful landscapes and mystical creatures. The kingdom was ruled by a kind and fair queen, who loved nothing more than to spend her days exploring the vast and varied terrain of her realm.

One day, the queen was wandering through a particularly cold and snowy region of the kingdom when she came upon a strange sight. Instead of snow, the ground was covered with soft, fluffy balls of wool, as if the earth itself had been transformed into a giant ball of yarn.

The queen was fascinated by this curious phenomenon, and she decided to follow the trail of wool to see where it led. After walking for some time, she came upon a beautiful lake, the surface of which was frozen solid. But instead of ice, the lake was made entirely of woolen fibers, swirling and twirling in the gentle breeze.

The queen marveled at the sight, and she couldn't help but reach out and touch the soft, velvety surface of the woolen lake. As she did, she felt a warmth and comfort wash over her, as if the wool were alive and pulsing with energy.

Over the years, the queen visited the woolen lake often, always feeling a sense of peace and contentment when she was near it. And as the years went by, the people of the kingdom began to flock to the woolen lake, seeking the same sense of warmth and comfort that the queen had found.

The woolen lake became a beloved and sacred place in the kingdom, and it was known throughout the land as the "mar de l√£" - the sea of wool. And so it remained, a magical and mystical place that brought joy and happiness to all who visited."
_AI GPT

Made with <3 and p5.js

metadata.name: codeTurning 1: Dotting #32
metadata.description:
The codeTurning project aims to reflect my journey from traditional tools to code, in which any day I learn a new skill.
Join me towards something new for me. Something different from the previous. 
Sometimes we will stand on the shoulders of giants.
 
Let's explore and see how far we get.
 
Lesson 1: Dotting
 
This is my first step.
The dotting series explores the technique of painting with dots-of-paint placed pseudo-randomly on the canvas.
 
------------
Thanks to Dario, Fernando, Alejandro, Piter, Diego, Manuel and Anthony for their support, especially for helping me to set up my project in the fxhash infrastructure.

metadata.name: Emergence IV #3
metadata.description:
A generative Pico-8 #tootcart to bring in the new year. Click/tap to move forward in a sequence unique to your generator. 

The emergence series focuses on using minimal algorithms with high randomness + entropy locking in order to create pleasing emergent patterns.

Missing me on twitter? I'm mostly on Mastodon now! Check it out and join the fun: https://genart.social/@aebrer


Source Code:
_set_fps(60)
r=rnd
p=srand
d=.9f=.9s=r(-1)p(s)
pal({-8,8,9,10,11,12,2},1)poke(24364,r({0,5,6,7}))cls()b=0c=1x=-8y=-8poke(0x5f2d,1)::_::
if(r()>d and r()>f)p(s)
x+=r(4)-2
y+=r(4)-2
b-=.0005
c+=r(.01)
x%=128y%=128
pset(x,y,c%8)
pset(y,x,c%8)
if(stat(34)==1and 0>b)s+=1cls()b=9poke(24364,r({0,5,6,7}))
if(stat(34)==2and 0>b)b=9extcmd("video")
if(t()%120==0)s+=1cls()b=9poke(24364,r({0,5,6,7}))
goto _
